#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
        int main()
        {
            char *str = "hello, world\n";
            str[5] = '.';
            printf("%s\n", str);
            return 0;
        }
char str[] = "hello, world\n"; creates a modifiable array with enough space to hold the string.
Now, str[5] = '.'; modifies the 6th character of the string, which is allowed because str is a mutable array, not a string literal.
The program will print "hello. world".
